","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>abbod</i>, <i>abbot(t)</i>, <i>abbat</i> ‘abbot’ (Old English <i>abbod</i>) or Old French <i>abet</i> ‘priest’. Both the Old English and the Old French term are derived from Late Latin <i>abbas</i> (genitive <i>abbatis</i>) ‘priest’, from Greek <i>abbas</i>, from Aramaic <i>aba</i> ‘father’. The nickname was presumably a joking reference to a person's behaviour. In the US, the English name is also sometimes a translation of a cognate or equivalent European name, e.g. Italian   Abate  , Spanish   Abad  , or German   Abt  .","History: George Abbot from Yorkshire, England, settled in Andover, MA, in 1640; he had numerous prominent descendants. George Abbott (probably not the same man) died in Rowley, MA, in 1647. Another early migrant was James Abbott, who came from Somerset, England, to Long Island, NY, in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Abate","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Antonio, Carmelo, Carmine, Gaetano, Vito, Angelo, Canio, Rocco, Sal, Aldo, Carlo.","Italian: from <i>abate</i> ‘priest’ (from Late Latin <i>abbas</i> ‘priest’, genitive <i>abbatis</i>). It could be a nickname, perhaps given to someone who behaved in a priest-like manner, an occupational name for the servant of a priest, or it may denote an (illegitimate) son of a priest. Compare   Labate  ."]},{"name":"Abbot","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Abbott  . The spelling with one <i>-t</i> is more typically Scottish than English, and in Gaelic-speaking areas of Scotland, this is sometimes an Anglicized form of   McNabb  ."]},{"name":"Abbitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Abbott  ."]},{"name":"Abbett","meanings":["English: variant of   Abbott  ."]},{"name":"Abbotts","meanings":["English:","topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>(atte) abbotes</i> ‘(at the, of the) abbot's (house or quarters)’, a name for someone who lived or worked at such a place, presumably a servant.","variant of   Abbott  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Agnes Abbott was born in 1385, in Farthinghoe, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir John Symond Abbott III in 1405. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died about 1443, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 59, and was buried in London, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1385–c.1443":"1385–umbes 1443","1382–1482":"1382–1482","1407–1486":"1407–1486","1408–1473":"1408–1473","1385–1443":"1385–1443","1448":"1448","c.1443":"umbes 1443","1443":"1443","1486":"1486","1385":"1385","1473":"1473","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Farthinghoe, Northamptonshire, England":"Farthinghoe, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1385–c.1443":"1385–noin 1443","1382–1482":"1382–1482","1407–1486":"1407–1486","1408–1473":"1408–1473","1385–14